  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and around me. Growing up in a neighborhood where many people were immigrants and worked hard to build a better future, I remember watching my classmates struggle with math and science because they felt like they didn't belong in those classes. When teachers or peers said, 'You're not cut out for this,' it wasn't just about the subject—it was about the fear that their identity would be judged. As a non-binary person who's worked part-time as a delivery driver in Philly, I've seen how stereotypes can make people feel invisible. For example, when I'm asked if I'm 'good at numbers' or if I 'should be in engineering,' it's not just a question—it's a microaggression that can make someone feel like they're failing before they even start. I think we absolutely should address stereotype threat in STEM. It's not just about fixing the system—it's about making sure everyone feels safe to try and succeed. How? Well, I've found that small things matter a lot. When I teach my kids to build things with LEGO, I try to emphasize creativity over perfection. In my own life, I've learned that when people feel seen and valued, they're more likely to take risks. So, instead of focusing on the problem, we should focus on building environments where everyone feels like they belong. It's not just about changing the system—it's about changing how we talk about it. When someone says, 'You don't belong here,' we need to respond with something like, 'You do belong here, and I'm here to help.' That's how we fix it.",
